segments.text: Have you ever been tempted to do announcing other than at Kyle Field?
In other words, do radio broadcasts?
Or has there ever been an opportunity to do that?
When you say have I been tempted, I was asked yesterday by a gentleman in this town to go over here.
I won't say where here is.
but I don't think I will.
Yes, I'd like it, I think, but I don't think I will.
Yeah, I've thought about that kind of stuff.
You know, one thing about some of these people on some of these programs, I don't mean the top fellas, but
They don't pronounce the names of the athletes, and they mumble sometimes.
And I think it's only common courtesy that you learn how to pronounce the names of the men you're dealing with.
I try to find out.
I do find out how to pronounce all the names of these.
Oh, I make mistakes.
Everybody does, of course, and I make more than most people.
The mistakes I make, the fans don't see.
What I was wondering about is, for example, for years, all of the Southwest Conference football games had been broadcast on the radio.
Yeah.
But I wondered if you had ever had an inclination to be involved in, say, the broadcast of some of the A&M games, or if you ever had been involved.
No.
You see that right next to me.
Uh-huh.
No, I, yeah, I think I kind of like it, just tell you the truth.
I'm getting pretty old, though, you know, to get mixed up with that kind of stuff.
Now, most people may not realize it, but it's pretty tense work up there.
It's pretty tense.
You can't get up there and look around at the seagulls and look around at the fan.
You're going to watch what's going on down there all the time, see?
And I have two spotters, and
Every once in a while, you know, they'll be gazing over there at some girl over across the way, and I'll say, who had the ball there?
I said, let's watch the ball game, you know, for a little while, and you've got to spot it over there.
Now, let's, you know, kind of watch.
But I've had pretty good spotters all the way along.
Pretty good boys.
But I check them.
I have to check them.
And then I want them to check me.
So you have two spotters, one for each school?
No, no.
No.
Yeah, one for each team.
I do not want anybody up there from the opposition school.
I want two Aggies, and I'll take this fellow, take A&M, and this fellow, take the other club.
And he keeps the both club on offense and defense.
Now, he's got speed cards there.
They issue us speed cards, and it's easy to, you know, all you got to do is get the number and the name right there.
Left speed cards on the offense and the depth on offense, speed cards on defense, depth on defense, and then the whole roster.
And every once in a while you look out there and you'll see 96.
It's not here.
Well, that doesn't happen very often.
It may be that somebody tears a jersey or something.
They haven't had time to come up and let us know that there's been a change in jerseys or maybe a muddy field.
That's fun, doing a game in mud.
That's a guessing game.
And I like to have two guys up there that can tell
By the way the fellow walked out there, who he is, never mind his number.
I couldn't tell.
I don't see him that often.
But I'm going over in a few days.
They're going to start, what do you call it, tomorrow.
Start to call workouts.
You know what I'm going to do when I get through here?
You don't need to put this on the table.
You were saying you were going to go over to the athletic department in a few days and...
I'll watch the scrimmages out there and familiarize myself with the ballplayers.
But I go there a day early and get the program and I take it home and I look it over and
I had one kiddo in a class.
I get quite a few athletes in a class.
I used to.
And this kiddo, I was mispronouncing his name.
So he came into one of my classes one day.
I was told what his name was by over there.
And I called the roll, and I called it this way.
And then I said, is that right?
pronounce a kiddo's name and then ask them, is that right?
And I want them to pronounce their name, because I think it's sinful to mispronounce a person's name.
It's their name, and they can have it pronounced any way they want to.
And so this kiddo said, no, it's pronounced thus and so.
I said, all right.
So every day from then on, I'd pronounce it wrong, and then under my breath, I'd pronounce it right, you know.
They got a big boot on their hands.
Have you ever recorded any of your broadcasts from Kyle Field?
No, I haven't.
No.
I don't know if anybody has.
No, not to my knowledge.
I don't think that he would very much.
I don't know.
I think for, say, 25 years, to all Aggies, you've been the voice of Kyle Field.
And I was wondering if there was any consideration being given to encourage you for posterity, particularly your opening remarks.
I don't think posterity.
Oh, I had a fellow come in here from somewhere, I don't know, somewhere on a campus.
He was doing a...
doing a movie or some kind of a thing, and he asked me if I would repeat that, give that line.
And he set up his stuff, and I gave it to him two or three times, and he locked his kit up and went off.
And I haven't seen him since.
But other than that, I don't... How long ago was this?
I don't know.
A few years ago.
A few years ago.
Was that...
I don't even remember who he was now or what he was...
cooked up with, but some department here on the county.
It could have been architecture.
Could have been.
Well, they did a movie here a few years ago, kind of a recruiting film.
I've seen parts of it.
What was the name of that?
Focus on the Future, I believe, was what?
I don't know whether that one's been in or not.
I believe when I called you, I indicated I was talking with former students
retired or retiring faculty members, and you're due to retire in a very few days, what plans do you have for the future?
Will you be continuing with theater arts in at all?
No, I don't have any plans of doing any future work in theater.
I dearly love it.
I'd really like, really, and this is what I'd really like to do, I'd like to do some more acting, but
I cannot remember lines.
When I first started in, you know, we had some good directors up there, and he had sling in a book.
I said, I want act one tomorrow night.
We'd memorize an act a night, and we'd get a show ready in pretty short order and do it quite well.
It's not stage fright, as far as I'm concerned.
I can talk to a
a bunch of people.
I'm not staged, right?
But I cannot, for some reason or other, remember lying.
That strange thing happened a few years ago.
We were doing a great big show in Guyana with Mrs. Morgan, and I took part.
She had two one-act plays, and they were part of it.
We had choruses.
We had everything.
And I made up a little scene.
It was a big thing.
We filled iron twice.
I had about a couple of thousand people in there both times.
It only holds 1,775.
And I played with Mrs. Delaplane with one scene.
And I was playing with Harry Gooding in another.
I forget the names of the little shows now.
And I was directing the whole thing at the same time.
And there was a table.
And I was playing the devil.
the naughty fella.
And there was a table here, and Harry was sitting here.
It was J.
Best Stone, I believe was the name of the thing.
And I came over.
I had all my stuff on the table, all my lines pasted on the table very neatly.
And I came over, you know, and I looked down there.
The stage kids had taken all that stuff off, and there I was without a single solitary line.
So we got through the scene somehow.
Now, I probably won't.
I'm going to spend a great deal of my time from now on working with orphans, kiddos without a mom and a papa.
Now, there are not very many people that ever stop to think about
kiddos without a mama and a papa.
I know these Texas orphanages are pretty well fixed.
They're run, a lot of them, by churches.
And they feed them well, and they clothe them well, and they go to public schools.
Some of them have their own schools.
And they live in little cottages, and they have a house mother, and they have many, many conveniences.
I know all of that.
And they're treated beautifully.
Some of them treated much better than they would be at home.
And some of them have a mother and a father.
Some of them have one, some have the other.
And some of the kiddos don't want, they've been given up.
Their folks don't want them, and that's why they land in these homes.
Well, I'm in contact now with three different homes here in Texas.
That's what they call them, homes.
And what I want to do is to spend a little time going around, if possible, that's what this last call was about, making little talks to these little churches around the area here.
I'm not going to go out there and cry.
I'm not going to bleed.
I'm not going to beg for anything.
I'm just going to put down the cold facts and issue them a little challenge.
I want to do something personal for these little kids, the little squirts.

Now, don't you think a little six-year-old girl would love to have a pair of cute little panties all her own or a little necklace or a little bracelet or a barrette or something, and a boy would like to have a little, I don't know, T-shirt or something like that that is his, and he gets it with his name on it as a present from somebody.
Now, that's what I want to do.
But I want to be very careful, and I'm going to proceed very slowly at this thing.
I want to be very careful that the people, a group of people in any church, don't do it just one time.
I want it to continue.
I want them to take an interest in this one cottage.
And there are anywhere from 8 to 10 to 12 kiddos in a cottage.
And I don't want every kiddo in there to get something at the same time.
You know, I don't want this kiddo to get something.
And most of them, sometimes they'll have a six-year-old girl, a 16-year-old girl, and they mix them up in a kind.
So it's more like a family rather than have all six-year-olds in one cottage.
But that's what I want to do in brief.
And it's going to take me a little bit of time to get the thing organized.
and to get it in operation.
But that's what I want to do.
And I'd like to have these people go visit these kids once in a while.
Boy, you...
I don't know.
Where I was, I don't know.
This had nothing to do with this, but it does in a way.
For years, in the past, I took stuff to orphanages, but it was just a truckload of this stuff and a truckload of that.
Nothing personal, see?
And I can remember when I was in the orphanage, it was in 23 Toby Street, Providence, Rhode Island.
I can remember that.
As I say, I can't remember what happened last week, but I can remember very vividly
Many, many, many things that happened 60 years ago in that place.
It was, we were, well, I'm not going to go into gory details of it, but I remember one time they had bars on the window of our playroom.
And I remember one time gripping those bars and looking out there and I said, if I ever get out of here, I'm going to burn this place down.
Well, I finally got taken out.
I wasn't adopted, but I was taken out for some unknown reason.
And about six months after I got out of there, the place burned down.
And I was about 25 miles from there, up in Massachusetts, out in the country.
And I ran out.
I ran away.
I ran out in the woods, and I spent all day out in those woods.
And I came in late at night, and a lady asked me where I'd been, and I told her.
I knew they were coming after me.
Oh, boy, I was scared.
I knew they were going to get me.
But that's what I want to do.
That's what I want to spend a considerable part of my time doing.
Because I am not going to go home and sit and wither.
That's what you'll do if you go home and sit.
Or if you don't have something to occupy yourself.
You can get in and ride around here, walk here, visit here, visit there.
But I feel that if a person is able...
He better stay active as long as he can.
What you have outlined is certainly a worthwhile endeavor, certainly a contribution to...
I am not doing this for my own sake.
Let me tell you something.
I have a reputation, I guess, of being very mean.
At least my students think I'm mean.
And I presume I am, but I got a lot of that stuff...
early in life, and a lot of it hasn't brushed off and it never will.
This is something that needs to be done, in my opinion.
It needs to be done.
Therefore, I want to do it.
It's nothing to me.
I want to stay out of the picture.
I don't want to be mentioned at all.
I just want to be the igniter.
Well, I didn't even imply that I thought you were doing it.
No, no, I know you didn't.
No, I know you didn't.
But that's how deeply I feel about this thing.
It has to be done.
And somebody, oh, I know a lot of these churches do a lot of these things at Christmas.
Now, don't you think it'd be a good idea to send somebody to the offense?
Yeah, Christmas, they get a ton of candy.
What I'm concerned about is the 13th of July.
I'm concerned about the 20th of March.
I'm concerned about the 10th of October.
Now, you don't have to send them a present every day, but they ought to get something occasionally to let them know that somebody out there knows that they're in here.
That's the thing, you see.
That's the thing that's important to me.
Then on the other end of the deal, they keep these kiddos until they get through high school.
Now on the other end of the deal, I am going to make a valiant effort to see if I can't find agency somewhere or money available somewhere where some of these worthy kids can go to college.
Now, there's a lot of money hanging around at various universities that nobody seems to know anything about in the form of little scholarships.
And they're not all based on academic excellence.
They're based on need.
And if anyone needs assistance, some of these little fellas getting out of these places have been in there 10 years or more.
They need it.
And that's the other end of the picture that I'm going to look into.
I've helped quite a few kids through school, but that's nobody's business.
But now that I've got time, that's what I want to do, and I think I'm going to feel pretty good doing it.
I mean, because it needs to be done.
That's what I mean.
There's too many of us, you know, we talk about helping our fellow man, but what do we do?
We sit in our can and... Now, I just came back from a trip up the Lake of the Ozarks, and me and my wife, we met one of our kiddos up there and our grandkids, and we spent a few days up there.
And I looked around at all of the facilities at these semi-rich people.
Now, they weren't rich, but there they were playing.
which is all right.
I maintain that a person never should forget how to play.
You should never grow up all the way.
I tell my students that all the time.
They sit there and snicker.
Now, this afternoon, I play out in my backyard every time I get a chance.
I'm this afternoon.
I can't wait to get out there and mow and do a little digging.
I got a little garden out there and no grow much, but I have a lot of fun.
Get out there and sweat and play.
That's what I call it.
Sit and talk to the birds and the cats and the dogs and
Bunny Squirrel, that little son of a gun, he's in there every day.
Every time I turn around, there he is.
Out there having a lot of fun.
I talk to him.
And I ask my students, I said, you ever talk to yourself?
And they look at me like I'm half nuts.
And finally, they'll admit that most of them do talk to themselves.
And they said, do you?
I said, yeah, I don't know anybody smarter than I am.
I get a lot of fun talking to me.
I got all the answers.
I got all the questions.
And I just sit there and puff my pipe.
And I have a lot of fun talking to myself, because I give myself the right answers.
But that's what I intend to do.
I've had a couple of jobs offered to me.
I had one.
I won't mention who it is.
It probably won't open up until another six or eight months.
But it's a public relations thing.
You know, a little thing.
You can't afford to take a job that pays you any money.
Well, the government will take it right away from you, you know what I mean?
Well, I'm all set up now to draw my pension and my Social Security, and I think I've earned them both.
I've put in many thousands of dollars in both of them.
And I'm not too anxious to...
I'm anxious to go to work for these fellas so I can meet people and have a lot of fun, but I don't want any, you know, no great money for it because...
The more you get, the more they take away from you.

Well, and as far as meeting people, I would say that the more people you can meet, the more contacts you have for your other project of working, in a sense, for the orphanages, or for the benefit of them, for the kids in the orphanages.
You see, I don't want money.
I don't want money.
I don't want people to give me any money.
I wouldn't know what to do.
Well, I'd know what to do with it, but...
I want to make it a personal thing.
Well, you're wanting things for the kitchen.
Little things.
They don't have to be big things.
Little things a kid will get and he'll open it.
He said, gee, my name is on this.
This is for me.
And he opens it up there and there it is.
Gosh, this is mine.
It's not a truckload of stuff from a hardware store or department store that they buy and just, here's yours, James.
Here's yours, Jack, and so forth.
It's just a personal thing.
You don't know how much that would mean to a kid to get some little, small thing, a couple of bucks or something like that.
Every once in a while, it's his own.
I can remember.
We never got any in my place.
Everything belonged to the orphanage, and you used it.
Well, it didn't belong to anybody.
As I say, all our clothes were secondhand when we got them.
secondhand toothbrush, everything.
Never got enough to eat.
Now, I'm not complaining.
Now, don't misunderstand me.
I'm just stating facts.
And in the wintertime, because it was winter up there, they had a big room there that had cloaks, they called a cloak room, sweaters and coats and so forth.
You had one pair of pants, and that's what they wore, them knee things and long black stockings and a shirt and underwear, long underwear.
And when it was cold, we went down in a cloak room.
And we'd fight.
Nobody had anything that belonged to him.
There was always a fight.
I walked out of there one morning with six sweaters.
I learned to fight in that office.
I was only a little squirt.
I was only six, seven years old.
And they used to take us to Sunday school.
Line us up, two by two.
March down to Sunday School.
I remember that very vigorously.
And the old lady there, she'd walk along with a thing.
It looked like an umbrella, but it was a club.
And they'd get down there, and they'd tell us about the sweet little Jesus.
I said, that's fine.
But I never heard any of that the rest of the week.
They just wailed us and we worked.
Now, I'm not making this up, buddy.
I'm sure you're not.
Now, there's no comparison between the place I was in and the place these kiddos are in now.
But I've been to quite a few of these homes and they're beautiful.
Some of them are absolutely, almost luxurious, you know.
But they worked us.
Inspect, inspect.
We went to the public school.
And you think we didn't have our problems there?
I'm sure you did.
You think we didn't have our fights there?
We haven't.
Even though Providence is a fairly sizable city and...
It has its slum areas.
Well, what I'm about to say is that there was no way to keep it a secret as to where you were coming from.
Oh, no.
They could tell by looking at you, you stinking little ragamuffin.
I mean, we were fighting with our classmates.
That's what I mean.
The kids was in the room.
And a kid will come up to see you and on the playground he says, I'll get you.
That means he's going to get you on the way home.
And he'll lay for you.
That was the term.
I'm going to lay for you.
And he's but one way home.
And you had a fight on the way home.
Then you get home and they're wondering why you got a bloody nose or something.
Then you have to lie about that.
But if you told them the truth, they'd give you another walloping for fight.
For fight, yeah.
I mean, you couldn't win, too.
You know, you couldn't win.
It was right next to a railroad where they had a lot of, you know, railroad, what do you call it, where all the trains were.
Footyard?
Yeah.
And this is a big freight area.
I've seen kids run away from that.
And I saw them when they brought them back.
And they stuck them in solitary for a while.
And I was tempted to run away.
But I was smarter than that.
I knew I didn't have any place to go.
I mean, the cops are going to pick you up very shortly.
And they know where you're from.
They caught you right there.
So I didn't try to run away.
I was smart enough to know I didn't have any place to go.
When you came back.
Yeah, you bet your life was worth it.
And they had, they also had, they had boys and girls there too, but I didn't know at that age, I didn't know a boy from a girl.
But I do remember we lined up here and they lined up over there.
And I looked straight ahead.
I mean, I didn't even know what a girl was.
But I do remember I was a big boy.
And each big boy had a little boy to give him a bath on Saturday.
And I had a little guy named Eddie Egan.
And he didn't want to take a bath, and I'd chase him all over that plain, have to rip his clothes off.
And they had these zinc bathtubs.
I don't know whether you ever saw one of them.
Zinc inside and wood on the outside.
You get a little corner ripped up on that, and you skate along that, it'll tear you up pretty good.
Well, I'd get him in there, and there'd be about eight or ten kids take a bath in the same bath water.
I'd finally get him in there, and I'd rub soap all over his eyes.
And after you get him in there, he gets slippery.
And I tried to drown him three or four times, but I never could drown him.
I'm not kidding you.
I'm saying, oh, he made, man, I'm telling you, I'd beat that kid half to death.
I wonder whatever became of him.
He was about, well, he was about two years old, three years old, I mean.
That little son of a gun, I'm telling you, we had him around and around every Saturday.
I can imagine.
I had a couple boys at two with him.
Well, actually, I guess they were more interested in taking him back as a place to play, but they had not had six other people in the water before.
We didn't have any play with him.
The funny thing was, I was six, seven years old, and I was a big boy.
I was a big boy.
And I had that little son of a gun.
And that was one of my jobs, give him a bath every Saturday.
And he'd fight and kick and holler.
I mean, that place was a bedlam.
It was a bedlam.
Because each big boy had a little boy to give him a bath.
And sometimes we'd get two in a tub and exchange them and knock their heads together and do all kinds of... Oh, we were mean.
I mean, you know, I mean... Well, in a sense, you were passing down the treatment that was handed out to you, I guess.
Yes, I guess so.
Well, anyway, that has nothing to do with what I'm going to do in the future.
And I'm sure these kiddos don't go through the same stuff we went through.
But I do know that they would love dearly to get some little...
some little remembrance every once in a while from somebody to let them know that somebody thinks of me once in a while.
That's all I want to do on a very small scale.
I'm sure that the way everything you say is true, and they certainly will appreciate it.
More than likely, they won't know who was the instigator.
No, I don't want them to know that.
That's none of their business.
I just want them to know that John got a present from Mrs. Brown.
I just want to steer up Mrs. Brown a little.
Oh, I'm going to visit these places.
I know that the two of the superintendents, I've met them before, years back.
But this one down in San Antonio, that's the one that intrigues me.
Because they need it more than anywhere else, any other often in the state that I know anything about.
But as I go along, the good Lord willing, I'll find out more about this stuff.
Do what I can.
I'm sure you will have plenty to do.
Well, I'm going to give it a try.
